Robert Cloutier, fifty-seven, has spent half of his life as an inmate at Stateville Correctional Center in Joliet, Illinois. Incarcerated for nearly forty years, Cloutier has one of the more dangerous prison jobs during the pandemic: Disposing of the prison’s biohazard waste. Since the onset of COVID-19 last March, this has meant collecting the facility’s used personal protective equipment.

At the start of the pandemic, Cloutier said he would fill several bags with discarded PPE. These days, he can make five stops around the prison and only pick up one or two gloves, maybe a mask.

Everything he gathers goes into an unused room, where used PPE has been amassing since the beginning of the coronavirus pandemic.
