South Side Weekly sent inmates at Stateville questions about their experiences during the pandemic and feelings about the vaccinations. Thirteen wrote back: All knew at least one person who had contracted the virus. Three tested positive for COVID-19; three others experienced symptoms but were not tested at the time.

Despite receiving educational materials about the vaccine, distrust of prison officials and strained relationships with prison medical services complicate some the thirteen inmates’ feelings about getting vaccinated against COVID-19. 

But while not entirely enthusiastic about the vaccine, they fear the alternative is worse.

“For me it’s not a matter of trust per say,” Stateville inmate William La’Roy Peeples Jr., fifty-six, wrote in his response. “It is about me feeling safer taking it, than trapped behind steel and concrete with the virus running rampant and having zero protection from it.”

Inside overcrowded prisons, it is nearly impossible to social distance. Inmates have seen prison officials disregard safety precautions and ignore pleas for help. 
